Anonymous Sun 09 May 2021 10:41:51 No.38543946 Report
Quoted By: >>38546019 >>38546565 >>38548506
>>38542216
All right. Cool. I don't mind helping out if I can. Just didn't want to be pouring water down a dry well.

When I see the words "world building," my go to questions are: explain the origin. If I'm writing, I need a solid structure in my head (or in a text file) that keeps me from inventing contradictions from the beginning. So, I want to know if this is a world of one species (of monkey, for example). Which lets me use our real world as a model. Humans out-competed & out-bred everything else even close to us, but even 40,000 years ago there appears to have been four or five species of sapient human anthros living together on this planet. I like to spend a lot of time exploring what that must have been like, and what if (for example) even three of them had been "equal enough" to have survived into the modern age? What sort of world would be living in now? So there's that question: how many closely related species/sub-families, etc. sharing sapience? Are they close enough to interbreed?

Then, are there other species that are far outside each others' family trees? Like, three interbreeding monkey types, but also two interbreeding wolf types, a fox type, and three cat types? How radically does that change dynamics?

Monkey girls had better be cute to be wort the effort. Just sayin'. What special features do they have? Tails? Full body fur/hair? Partial? Tails? At all? Short? Long? What are their feet like? Do they have bright blue baboon butts? I wanna know.

And I want to know how that affects their societies. Group marriages? Tribes or nations? How do they raise children? What tech level? Space monkeys or pirate monkeys? Or space pirate monkeys? What's their music and art like? Their architectural designs? What agriculture do they have, or are missing?

World building is usually making a long list of questions and then answering them, or marking them irrelevant. And, at this point, I've just assumed they live on an alternate Earth.

Hey sorry, that wasn't my intention. But honestly, I get you. I feel that way over so many artists myself. But neither of us should worry. You're on an ever rising ladder and every stroke of the pen you make will take you higher. I say it won't take you too long to improve and look at my picture again and laugh at how this used to impress you. Don't forget that there was a point in time where me and really every other artist made work woefully inferior to yours. The key is staying at it and so far you're doing a great job with that.

As for my setup: At the very beginning all I had was a stack of printer paper, a bulk pack of the cheapest HB pencils I could find and a dream.
After that I upgraded to a Wacom Bamboo and (a totally legal copy of) Photoshop, which is what I was using until a few weeks ago.
Now I use a Huion Kamvas 16 Pro (I got lucky with a super good deal, it was way too expensive for me otherwise) and Clip Studio Paint for software.

If you're looking to upgrade (assuming your current setup isn't adequate) I'd first recommend Krita. It's art software that is free and almost as good as the options out there. As for tablets, a 12-inch Huion or XP-Pen tablet (60-100 bucks depending on the model) should last you a good few years.

Hope I could help, whatever you do, you got this!
